## Reflection

My experience with Suno revealed that there is a lot still left to be desired in terms of how AI processes genre, sonic textures and the intention. The strongest takeaway is that it has an inherent bias towards clean and polished audio. When trying to replicate things that sound "ugly" or "raw", the AI would sanitize it too much. Even with specific prompts, it was aggressively cleaned up.

When I provided text, it ultimately missed the mark. When I provided audio. it was able to recognize harmonic and melodic components but still lacked textural grit. When combining both, it still proved Suno is incapable of generating anything authentic sounding.

With the intention of creating something popier, Suno was a lot more successful. Being able to fine-tune certain setting such as weirdness and how much the original audio or stylistic influences changed the track was able to give me closer results, but I felt like I was forced to work with it's constraints rather than create something I truly enjoy.








